The issue you are facing is related to the asynchronous nature of state updates in React. The `setObligationForm` function, which is used to update the state, does not immediately reflect the updated value. Therefore, when you log the `obligationForm` immediately after setting it, you may not see the updated value.

To overcome this, React provides a callback function as the second parameter to the state updater function. You can utilize this callback to perform any actions that rely on the updated state value. Here's an updated version of your code:

```javascript
const handleSaveObligationForm = (propName: string, value: any) => {
    setObligationForm(prev => ({ ...prev, [propName]: value }));
    console.log('obligationForm', obligationForm);
    // The console.log above may not show the updated state value

    // You can perform any actions that rely on the updated state here
    // For example, you can access the updated state using `obligationForm` variable
};
```

To access the updated state value immediately after it has been updated, you can use the `useEffect` hook with a dependency array. This will execute the effect whenever the `obligationForm` state changes. You can log or perform any further actions within the effect:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
    console.log('Updated obligationForm:', obligationForm);
}, [obligationForm]);
```

By using the `useEffect` hook with the dependency array, you can ensure that the log statement or other actions are executed whenever the `obligationForm` state is updated.

